<a name="Installation">

<H1>Installation
</H1>


<P>
<A name="index_2_1"></A>For using PerlPoint and pp2html you need the following components:
</P>

<UL>
<LI>Perl 5.6.0 or better</LI>
<LI>Storable</LI>
<LI>Digest::SHA1</LI>
<LI>Getopt::ArgvFile</LI>
<LI>PerlPoint-Package</LI>
<LI>PerlPoint-Converters</LI>
</UL>


<P>
To install a module you must do the following steps:
</P>

<OL>
<LI VALUE=1>Get the module form CPAN.</LI>
<LI>Unpack the tar.gz or .tgz file and cd to the new module directory, for example:</LI>
</OL>


<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=80%><TR><TD bgcolor="#e5e5e5"><PRE>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">
 % gunzip PerlPoint-Package-0.35.tgz
 % cd PerlPoint-Package-0.35
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TABLE>

<OL>
<LI VALUE=1>Make and install the package:</LI>
</OL>


<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=80%><TR><TD bgcolor="#e5e5e5"><PRE>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">
 % perl Makefile.PL
 % make test
 % make install
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TABLE>


<P>
If you do not have write permission in the standard Perl installation path you may install the modules in your home directory:
</P>


<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=80%><TR><TD bgcolor="#e5e5e5"><PRE>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">
 % perl Makefile.PL PREFIX=$HOME
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TABLE>


<P>
This will install the package somewhere in ./lib/perl5/... under your home. Don't forget to set <CODE>PERL5LIB</CODE> to include the corresponding paths. Otherwise the new modules will not be found in <CODE>@INC</CODE>.
</P>


<P>
<B>Special hint for NT or Win9x systems:</B>
</P>


<P>
Versions before 0.35 of <B>PerlPoint-Package</B> may have problems with the <CODE>--cache</CODE> option. Disable this option in the .cfg option files for the pp2html examples.
</P>
